        // ── Overview (Article) ───────────────────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Payments Overview",
            Slug = "payments-overview",
            Summary = "How to record customer payments, choose the payment method, apply money to invoices, and what changes when your books live in an outside accounting system.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 4,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 1,
            AppRoutes = """["/payments"]""",
            Tags = """["payments","accounting"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Payments Overview\n\nWhen a customer pays you, this is where you write it down. Payments records the money you take in — check, cash, card, wire — and marks the invoices it pays off, so your accounts-receivable (AR) picture stays current and you can tell at a glance who still owes you.\n\n### Do you run your own books, or an outside accounting system?\n\nIf your shop keeps its books inside Forge, you do it all here: record a payment, apply it to invoices, delete one you entered by mistake, and look back at what a customer has paid.\n\nIf your shop keeps its books in an outside accounting system such as QuickBooks Online, that system owns the payments instead. You'll see a blue notice at the top of the page, the Record Payment button goes away, and the payments you record over there flow into Forge for you to view. You can still open any payment to check the details — you just enter and change them in the accounting system, not here.\n\n### How the customer paid\n\nEvery payment notes how the money came in. Pick the one that matches:\n- **Cash** — bills and coins handed over\n- **Check** — a paper check (put the check number in Reference Number)\n- **Credit Card** — a card payment (Reference Number can hold the last four digits or the transaction ID)\n- **Bank Transfer** — an ACH or direct bank transfer\n- **Wire** — a wire transfer (Reference Number holds the wire confirmation)\n- **Other** — anything that doesn't fit above; note the details\n\n### Putting a payment toward invoices\n\nOne payment can pay off one invoice or several. For each invoice, you say how much of the payment goes to it. That covers the everyday cases:\n\n- **Pays an invoice in full** — the whole payment clears one invoice, which then shows as Paid\n- **Partial payment** — the customer sends part of what they owe; the invoice shows as Partially Paid and the rest stays outstanding\n- **One check, several invoices** — split the payment across each invoice the customer is settling\n- **Money in before the invoice** — record the payment now and leave it unapplied; the leftover shows as Unapplied (highlighted yellow) so you can put it toward an invoice later\n\nWhen the amount you put toward an invoice covers the whole balance, that invoice flips to Paid on its own. A partial amount moves it to Partially Paid. You never have to go mark the invoice yourself.\n\n### What you can't overdo\n\nThe amounts you apply can't add up to more than the payment itself — you can't hand out more money than came in. And the amount toward any one invoice can't be more than that invoice still owes, so you never accidentally overpay a bill. If a customer paid more than they owed, leave the extra unapplied and sort it out with them.\n\n### When you'll use this page\n\n- A customer's check, cash, or electronic payment lands and you need to record it\n- A big invoice gets paid down a little at a time\n- One customer payment settles several invoices at once\n- Money arrives before you've sent the invoice, and you want it tracked until you do\n- You need to look back at what a customer has paid and when","sections":[]}"""
        });

