            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Quiz,
            EstimatedMinutes = 5,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 4,
            AppRoutes = """["/payments"]""",
            Tags = """["payments","quiz","accounting"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"passingScore":80,"questionsPerQuiz":8,"shuffleOptions":true,"showExplanationsAfterSubmit":true,"questions":[{"id":"pmt1","text":"A customer mails you one check for $5,000 that covers two of their invoices. What's the cleanest way to record it?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Enter two separate payments of $2,500 each, one per invoice"},{"id":"b","text":"Click Record Payment, enter $5,000 as a Check, then add both invoices and split the amount across them","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Open each invoice, mark it Paid, then record one payment for the total"},{"id":"d","text":"Record one payment and leave it unapplied — Forge will match the invoices for you"}],"explanation":"One payment can settle several invoices. Record the single $5,000 check, choose Check as the method, then add each invoice and enter how much of the $5,000 goes to it. Recording it as one payment matches what actually came in — one check."},{"id":"pmt2","text":"A payment in the list shows an 'Unapplied' amount of $1,200 highlighted in yellow. What is it telling you?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"The payment bounced and $1,200 was returned"},{"id":"b","text":"$1,200 of the payment hasn't been put toward any invoice yet","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"The customer still owes $1,200 on this payment"},{"id":"d","text":"$1,200 went toward an invoice that was later cancelled"}],"explanation":"Unapplied is money you've received but haven't yet put toward a specific invoice. The yellow highlight is a reminder to go apply it — for example, once the matching invoice exists."},{"id":"pmt3","text":"You apply a payment that covers an invoice's whole remaining balance. What happens to that invoice?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"It's deleted"},{"id":"b","text":"It flips to Paid on its own","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Nothing — you still have to open it and mark it Paid"},{"id":"d","text":"It's archived and drops off the list"}],"explanation":"When your applied amount clears the full balance, the invoice moves to Paid automatically. Apply only part of the balance and it moves to Partially Paid. Either way you don't touch the invoice yourself."},{"id":"pmt4","text":"Your shop switches its books to QuickBooks Online. What changes on the Payments page?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Nothing — you always record payments here"},{"id":"b","text":"A blue notice appears saying QuickBooks handles payments, the Record Payment button goes away, and the page becomes view-only","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Your existing payments are wiped and replaced with QuickBooks ones"},{"id":"d","text":"The Payments page disappears from the menu"}],"explanation":"Once an outside accounting system keeps your books, it owns the payments. The page turns view-only with a blue notice, the Record Payment button is hidden, and payments you enter over there flow in for you to see. Your old records stay put."},{"id":"pmt5","text":"You open a payment to delete it, but there's no Delete button. Why not?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"You need the Admin role to delete payments"},{"id":"b","text":"The payment is applied to one or more invoices — take it off every invoice first","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Payments can never be deleted, only archived"},{"id":"d","text":"The payment came from an outside accounting system and can't be changed here"}],"explanation":"You can only delete a payment that isn't applied to anything. That guards the invoices it's tied to from silently changing. Remove it from each invoice, and the Delete button comes back."},{"id":"pmt6","text":"A customer wires you $3,000, but you haven't sent them the invoice yet. What's the right move?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Hold off — don't record the payment until the invoice exists"},{"id":"b","text":"Record it now as a $3,000 Wire with no invoices applied; the unapplied amount holds it until you can apply it","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Make a placeholder invoice for $3,000 and apply the payment to that"},{"id":"d","text":"Skip the payment and jot a note on the customer's record instead"}],"explanation":"Record the money when it arrives, even with no invoice ready. The full $3,000 shows as Unapplied (yellow in the list), easy to find and apply once you send the invoice."},{"id":"pmt7","text":"What is the Reference Number field for?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"It's the payment's own number, created for you"},{"id":"b","text":"It holds an outside reference like a check number, wire confirmation, or card transaction ID","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"It ties the payment to a sales order"},{"id":"d","text":"It's required for every method except Cash"}],"explanation":"Reference Number is optional and holds the customer's or bank's own reference — check number, wire confirmation, card transaction ID, ACH reference. You can search on it from the list. The payment's own number is separate and created for you."},{"id":"pmt8","text":"You try to put $2,000 of a payment toward an invoice that only owes $1,500. What happens?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"It goes through and leaves a $500 credit on the invoice"},{"id":"b","text":"It's blocked — you can't apply more than the invoice still owes","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"It applies $1,500 and leaves the other $500 unapplied for you"},{"id":"d","text":"It goes through and flags the invoice as overpaid"}],"explanation":"You can't apply more to an invoice than it owes, so you never overpay a bill by accident. Apply $1,500 to clear it, then put the remaining $500 toward another invoice or leave it unapplied."},{"id":"pmt9","text":"Which of these is NOT one of the payment methods you can pick?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Bank Transfer"},{"id":"b","text":"Wire"},{"id":"c","text":"PayPal","isCorrect":true},{"id":"d","text":"Other"}],"explanation":"The six choices are Cash, Check, Credit Card, Bank Transfer, Wire, and Other. For PayPal or anything else not listed, pick Other and describe it