        // ── Advanced Reference (Reference) ───────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Payments — Advanced Reference",
            Slug = "payments-reference",
            Summary = "Deeper tips for recording payments: handling a customer who pays in a different currency, why you can't post-date a payment, and what to do when a customer overpays.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Reference,
            EstimatedMinutes = 4,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 90,
            AppRoutes = """["/payments"]""",
            Tags = """["payments","reference","advanced"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## When a customer pays in a different currency\n\nMost shops invoice and get paid in one currency, and you'll never think about this. But if your shop deals in more than one currency, an extra **Settlement FX rate** box shows up next to each invoice as you apply the payment. It won't appear at all for a single-currency shop, so don't go looking for it if you don't see it.\n\nThink of it as the exchange rate the money settled at. It converts what the customer actually paid — in their currency — into your shop's home currency, so the invoice is credited the right amount in your books.\n\n- **Use the rate the bank actually gave you.** When a foreign payment clears, your bank settles it at a specific rate that day. Enter that rate here so the invoice shows exactly what you netted, not an estimate.\n- **Leave it at 1 for your home currency.** If the invoice is already in your shop's own currency, the rate is simply 1 — one dollar in is one dollar credited. That's the starting value, so you rarely change it for domestic payments.\n- **Set it per invoice.** If one payment covers several invoices that settled at different rates, you can enter the rate for each one separately.\n- **Picking up a saved draft.** If you'd started a payment earlier and saved it before this box existed, it comes back set to 1 — double-check it before you finish.\n\n## Why you can't date a payment in the future\n\nThe **Payment Date** is the day the money actually reached you, so the calendar won't let you pick a date later than today. That's on purpose: a payment you haven't received yet isn't a payment. Today is fine — the whole current day is open — but tomorrow and beyond are greyed out.\n\n- **A date is required.** You have to pick the day it came in before you can save.\n- **Recording a late entry?** Use the day the money actually arrived, even if you're keying it in a few days later. Back-dating to the real receipt date is expected; forward-dating isn't allowed.\n- **The date is what drives your aging.** Because payment dates land your money on the right day, your AR aging and month-to-date totals line up with the bank.\n\n## When a customer overpays\n\nSometimes a customer sends more than an invoice owes — a rounding slip, a duplicate check, or a deposit toward future work. You can't force the extra onto an invoice that doesn't owe it; the amount toward any one invoice stops at that invoice's balance.\n\nSo apply what clears the invoice and leave the rest **unapplied**. It sits on the payment, highlighted yellow, until you decide what to do — put it toward their next invoice, or refund it outside the app. Either way it's visible and accounted for, not lost.\n\n## A note on outside accounting systems\n\nEverything above only comes up when your shop keeps its own books in Forge. If your books live in an outside accounting system, you record payments over there instead — the whole record-payment screen, including the currency and date boxes, isn't shown here.","sections":[]}"""
        });

